The bundled AUI version is 3.4.2 (as seen in UPM), while the batched javascript file  /content/static/lpmgw6/concat.aui.a966b6ff10f28b440a7942a728a8dfe4.cache.js  contains this
{noformat}
 if(typeof jQuery!="undefined"){var AJS=(function(){var D=[];var C={version:"3.4.0",
{noformat}
which, I believe, means AUI 3.4.0.

The applink 3.5 bundled in FE 2.7 requires new API from AUI 3.4.2 so it is currently broken.

This document is outdated:
http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/FISHEYE/Associating+a+Group+with+a+Repository

As per the current functionality its under {{Administration -> Repositories -> REPO -> Permissions}} or under {{{Administration -> Defaults -> Permissions}}

The "Re-Sync" button for manual resync of the JIRA/Crowd authentication doesn't seem to do anything. It seems the crowd-resync button has not been hooked up appropriately:

{code}
<input type="button" id="crowd-resync" value="Re-Sync">
//...
AJS.$("#crowd-edit").click(function() {
  window.location = "resyncAuth.do";
});
{code}

Probably only needs changing to 

{code}
<input type="button" id="crowd-resync" value="Re-Sync">
//...
AJS.$("#crowd-resync").click(function() {
  window.location = "resyncAuth.do";
});
{code}

If I click on Source tab, click on a repository name, click on the Reports tab on the main screen, the Line chart is loaded, displaying in the date axis a date range like this:
{noformat}
Out-2009   Jan-2010   Abr-2010   Jul-2010 [...] Out-2011
{noformat}

However, if I mouse over one of the bars displayed between {{Jan-2010}} and {{Abr-2010}}, meaning that the activity is between these dates, a popup is displayed containing the text: {{38 file revisions between 2009-09-20 and 2009-09-27}}

Please see the image attached, where the mouse is hovering over the highest bar between {{Jan-2010}} and {{Abr-2010}} and displaying wrong data in the popup.

From SAC ticket, creating on customer's behalf:
{quote}
One of my users is complaining that they can only see a subset (20) of the diffs at a time for a particularly large commit (97 files). They'd like to be able to expand all onto a really long page and then perform a changeset-wide search. With the current behavior they have to click next and repeat the search on all pages to find the occurrences of a particular string. If there's no other view that will allow them to see the entire changeset (marked up in html) then there needs to be a config option for configuring the paging behavior or disabling it completely.
{quote}

